Section 1:
1 L.D. 634
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 STATE AND LOCAL GOVERNMENT
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 402, L.D. 634, “Resolve, to Establish
10 the Commission to Study the Reduction of Unfunded and Outdated Municipal and County
11 Mandates”
12 Amend the resolve by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
13 'Sec. 1. Commission established. Resolved: That the Commission to Study the
14 Reduction of Unfunded and Outdated Municipal and County Mandates, referred to in this
15 resolve as "the commission," is established.
16 Sec. 2. Commission membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint Rule
17 353, the commission consists of 15 members appointed as follows:
18 1. Two members of the Senate, appointed by the President of the Senate, including a
19 member from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
20 2. Two members of the House of Representatives, appointed by the Speaker of the
21 House, including a member from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats
22 in the Legislature;
23 3. One member representing the Governor's office, designated by the Governor;
24 4. A representative of a statewide association representing municipalities, appointed
25 by the President of the Senate;
26 5. A representative of a statewide association representing town and city clerks,
27 appointed by the Speaker of the House;
28 6. A representative of a statewide association representing county commissioners,
29 appointed by the President of the Senate;
30 7. A representative of a county with 100,000 or more residents, appointed by the
31 Speaker of the House;
32 8. A representative of a municipality with more than 20,000 residents, appointed by
33 the President of the Senate;
Page 1 - 132LR0816(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 402, L.D. 634
1 9. Two representatives of municipalities with 10,001 to 20,000 residents, one
2 appointed by the President of the Senate and one appointed by the Speaker of the House;
3 10. A representative of a municipality with 5,001 to 10,000 residents, appointed by the
4 Speaker of the House; and
5 11. Two representatives of municipalities with 5,000 residents or less, one appointed
6 by the President of the Senate and one appointed by the Speaker of the House.
7 Sec. 3. Chairs. Resolved: That the first-named Senate member is the Senate chair
8 and the first-named House of Representatives member is the House chair of the
9 commission.
10 Sec. 4. Appointments; convening of commission. Resolved: That all
11 appointments must be made no later than 30 days following the effective date of this
12 resolve. The appointing authorities shall notify the Executive Director of the Legislative
13 Council once all appointments have been completed. After appointment of all members,
14 the chairs shall call and convene the first meeting of the commission. If 30 days or more
15 after the effective date of this resolve a majority of but not all appointments have been
16 made, the chairs may request authority and the Legislative Council may grant authority for
17 the commission to meet and conduct its business.
18 Sec. 5. Duties. Resolved: That the commission shall review unfunded and outdated
19 municipal and county mandates in order to provide recommendations and to report out a
20 list of mandates for the Legislature to consider eliminating or revising.
21 Sec. 6. Staff assistance. Resolved: That the Legislative Council shall provide
22 necessary staffing services to the commission, except that Legislative Council staff support
23 is not authorized when the Legislature is in regular or special session.
24 Sec. 7. Interim report. Resolved: That, no later than December 3, 2025, the
25 commission shall submit to the Joint Standing Committee on State and Local Government
26 an interim report that includes its findings and recommendations, including suggested
27 legislation. The joint standing committee may report out legislation related to the report to
28 the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
29 Sec. 8. Final report. Resolved: That, no later than November 4, 2026, the
30 commission shall submit a final report that includes its findings and recommendations,
31 including suggested legislation, not included in the interim report under section 7 for
32 presentation to the joint standing committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over state
33 and local government matters. The joint standing committee may report out legislation
34 related to the report to the 133rd Legislature in 2027.'
35 Amend the resolve by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
36 section number to read consecutively.
37 SUMMARY
3388 This amendment changes the membership of the Commission to Study the Reduction
3399 of Unfunded and Outdated Municipal and County Mandates and removes the provisions
4400 that require 2 to 4 meetings annually and allow the commission to meet remotely. Instead
4411 of one report, the amendment requires an interim and a final report to the joint standing
Page 2 - 132LR0816(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 402, L.D. 634
412 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over state and local government matters,
423 which is authorized to report out legislation related to each report.
434 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
445 (See attached)
Page 3 - 132LR0816(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
